      Supporting sandbox · planted structure
    </div>
    <h1>Mini Causal Models — a sandbox with a known answer</h1>
    <p class="text-[var(--color-text-muted)] italic !text-lg !mb-8">
      Controlled planted-ground-truth infrastructure for the core program.
    </p>

    <p>
      Mini Causal Models are a controlled planted-ground-truth sandbox for the core program. They
      provide small causal structures whose true generating graph is known, so that structure
      recovery, <a href="/research/isotrace">Isotrace</a>-style path localization, and
      <a href="/research/ciy">CIY</a>-style quantitative grading can be tested against a known
      target.
    </p>

    <MiniCausalFigure />

    <p>
      The hard direction in my <a href="/writing/inferential-productivity">note on inferential
      productivity</a> is reverse: given a behavior, what is the <em>smallest</em> causal structure
      that has to be there? On a real model, there is usually no ground truth against which to score
      a recovered structure. The sandbox keeps the problem synthetic before trusting the method
      elsewhere: plant the graph, simulate data, train or evaluate a model on that data, and test
      whether behavioral recovery returns the structure that was actually planted.
    </p>

    <p>
      This is supporting infrastructure, not a fourth equal core paper. It exists to make the
      quantitative and structure-recovery parts of Hierarchical Causal Evidence falsifiable against
      a known answer.
    </p>

    <hr/>
    <p class="!text-sm !text-[var(--color-text-muted)]">An interactive sandbox — plant a structure, see what the recovery returns — will live here.</p>
  </article>
</Base>
